[[Category:qq-Kogaikuni Shrine-qq]]
]][[Category:Kogaikuni Shrine]]Kogaikuni Shrine, located in Aizuwakamatsu, Fukushima Prefecture, Japan, is a historic Shinto shrine with origins dating back to the 9th century. It is dedicated to deities associated with agriculture and sericulture, reflecting its deep-rooted connection to local silk cultivation. <ref name=":0">[https://anregblog.wordpress.com/2017/02/18/kogaikuni-jinja-the-survivor-aizuwakamatsu-2/ anregblog]</ref>The shrine enshrines Ukemochi-no-┼Їkami (С┐ЮжБЪтцДуЦъ), Waku-musubi-no-┼Їkami (уеџућБжюітцДуЦъ), and Amaterasu-┼Їmikami (тцЕуЁДтцДтЙАуЦъ). <ref name=":0" />Visitors are greeted by a traditional torii gate leading to serene, forested grounds. The main hall showcases traditional Shinto architecture with intricate wooden carvings and vibrant vermilion hues.<ref name=":1">[https://blog.dekitabi.com/2024/07/27/aizuwakamatsu-city-itinerary/ dekitabi Blog]</ref>Kogaikuni Shrine has been historically significant, receiving patronage from the Matsudaira family of Aizu, who rebuilt it in 1811 after a fire. <ref name=":0" />Remarkably, the shrine survived the Boshin War largely unscathed, despite being used as a command post during the conflict.<ref name=":0" />The shrine hosts various rituals and festivals throughout the year, offering visitors a glimpse into traditional practices and beliefs of the Aizu people. <ref name=":1" />Notably, the sacred tree, Minehari-zakura, over 1,000 years old, is designated as a natural monument.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DfDo81ZQCQM&utm_source=chatgpt.com</ref>]][[]]]][[Category:]]]][[ stubs]]]][[Category:]]]][[ stubs]]]][[Category:Unsorted completion categories]]

