'''Kogaikuni Shrine''' (сЂЊсЂїсЂёсЂЈсЂФсЂўсѓЊсЂўсѓЃ) is a Shinto shrine in Kogaimachi, {{ill|lt=Aizuwakamatsu|Q237699|qid=Q237699|1=Aizuwakamatsu}}, {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707|qid=Q71707|1=Fukushima Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}; under the modern ranking system, it was a {{ill|lt=kensha|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=prefectural shrine|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}. Its formal name is '''Kogaikuni Jinja''' (УаХжцітюІуЦъуцЙ), and it is also called '''Kogaigu'''. Its crest is the "Aizu Mitsu-aoi."<ref name="origin">Shrine origin record.</ref>

It is known as a shrine associated with sericulture.

=== Enshrined deities ===
The shrine enshrines the following three deities.<ref name="origin"/>
* {{ill|lt=Ukemochi|Q2280323|qid=Q2280323|lt=Ukemochi-no-Okami|1=Ukemochi}}
* {{ill|qid=Q10921330|lt=Wakumusubi|UNKNOWN|qid=Q10921330|lt=Wakumusubi-no-Okami|1=Wakumusubi}}
* {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|qid=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu-Omikami|1=Amaterasu}}

=== History ===
=== Foundation ===
According to shrine tradition, the shrine was founded in 811 (Konin 2).<ref name="origin"/>

In the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' {{ill|lt=Jinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmy┼Їch┼Ї}}, no other official shrine bears the name "Kogaikuni," making this name unique to this shrine. Scholars have argued that its foundation was related to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=sericulture|1=UNKNOWN}}, and that it may have reflected a central-government policy to promote sericulture in Aizu rather than merely local custom.{{Sfn|УџЋжцітЏйуЦъуцЙ№╝ѕуЦъсђЁ№╝Ѕ|1984}} As background, the ''{{ill|lt=Nihon Koki|Q1077029|qid=Q1077029|1=Nihon K┼Їki}}'' entry for November 8, 796 records that women from several provinces were dispatched to Mutsu for two years to teach sericulture techniques.{{Sfn|УџЋжцітЏйуЦъуцЙ№╝ѕуЦъсђЁ№╝Ѕ|1984}}

=== Historical outline ===
In the ''Engishiki Jinmyocho'' compiled in 927 (Encho 5), the shrine is listed as "Kogaikuni Shrine" in Aizu District, {{ill|lt=Mutsu Province|Q907389|qid=Q907389|1=Mutsu Province}}, and classified as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}.{{Sfn|УџЋжцітЏйуЦъуцЙ№╝ѕт╣│тЄАуцЙ№╝Ѕ|1993}} Of the Engishiki shrines in Aizu District, only Kogaikuni Shrine and {{ill|lt=Isasumi Shrine|Q3155136|qid=Q3155136|1=Isasumi Shrine}} are listed.{{Sfn|УџЋжцітЏйуЦъуцЙ№╝ѕт╣│тЄАуцЙ№╝Ѕ|1993}}

Although it is not clearly recorded in the official national histories, shrine tradition says it was elevated to an official shrine in the Jowa era (834-848) by petition of Fujiwara no Fujimaro, then Azechi and Commander of the Chinju-fu, and that shrine buildings were first established in 1011 by local officials including Ishibe Shosho Michihide.<ref name="origin"/> The buildings were later lost to warfare and declined, but were restored by {{ill|lt=Hoshina Masayuki|Q837236|qid=Q837236|1=Hoshina Masayuki}}, first lord of the {{ill|lt=Aizu Domain|Q4389944|qid=Q4389944|1=Aizu Domain}}, who also confirmed an endowment of 20 koku.<ref name="origin"/> In 1743 the shrine rank was raised to Shoichii; after another fire in 1807, it was rebuilt in 1819 by the 8th lord, {{ill|lt=Matsudaira Katataka|Q846200|qid=Q846200|1=Matsudaira Katataka}}.<ref name="origin"/>

After the Meiji Restoration, in November 1876 (Meiji 9), it was listed as a prefectural shrine in the modern shrine ranking system.{{Sfn|ТўјТ▓╗уЦъуцЙУфїТќЎ|1912}}

=== Precinct ===
The main sanctuary is in Oji-zukuri (also called Kumano-zukuri).<ref name="origin"/> Other structures include a heiden, haiden, shinsenjo, and kaguraden.<ref name="origin"/>

An old cherry tree standing before the haiden is said to be over 1,000 years old and 14 meters tall; it is especially called '''Minehari-zakura'''.<ref name="board">Precinct information board.</ref> Shrine tradition says it was planted when the shrine buildings were established in 1011.<ref name="board"/> It is designated a natural monument of Aizuwakamatsu City.<ref name="board"/>

